To find the substring that occurs only once in a given string, you can use the following approach in Java with the Apache Commons Lang StringUtils library:

First, create a list of all substrings that occur more than once using `splitByCharacter` and `groupingBy` from Java 8 Stream API. Then, find the substring that occurs only once by checking the size of each group.

Here's an example:

```java
import org.apache.commons.lang3.StringUtils;
import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String input = "the quick brown fox jumps over the lazy dog the quick brown fox";
        List<String> substrings = Arrays.asList(input.split("\\s+")); // Split by whitespace

        Map<String, Long> countMap = substrings.stream()
                .collect(Collectors.groupingBy(String::valueOf, Collectors.counting()));

        String uniqueSubstring = null;
        long count = -1;

        for (Map.Entry<String, Long> entry : countMap.entrySet()) {
            if (entry.getValue() == 1) {
                uniqueSubstring = entry.getKey();
                count = entry.getValue();
                break;
            }
        }

        System.out.println("The substring that occurs only once in the given string is: " + uniqueSubstring);
    }
}
```

